attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, for GNU/Linux 2.6.32, BuildID[sha1]=e21a4d2542eebc216784cb2c04522be74f23a8f6, not stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a Linux backdoor/Trojan that daemonizes upon execution and establishes communication with a Command and Control (C2) server. It uses libcurl for networking and gathers system information such as OS version (via lsb_release) and hostname. The malware maintains an XOR-obfuscated configuration file at '/etc/apdl.cf' and includes a comprehensive command dispatcher. Remote capabilities include arbitrary shell command execution (via popen), file exfiltration (upload), file delivery (download), directory traversal, and secure file deletion. It attempts to evade network detection by using a hardcoded Windows MSIE 10.0 User-Agent.
